Biophenome Linked Open Databases (BioLOD). Biophenome Linked Open Databases. last accessed: 17-Nov-2014. Industry link to Biophenome Linked Open Databases (BioLOD) - providing access to genes and bio-resources. Data includes observable characteristics and behavior (phenotypes) that has been reported in literature, annotations and the like. Data can be downloaded in RDF format. Users can register novel phenotypic information that relates to each resource. Data is organized by ontological hierarchies based on semantic web technology standards including LOD (Linked Open Data), OWL and OBO (Web Ontology Language and Open Biomedical Ontology). BioLOD plans to provide a variety of tools and workflows to work with this data. URL: http://biolod.jp/.

WEB248

Princeton University. WordNet - lexical database for English. last accessed: 17-Nov-2014. Industry link about WordNet - lexical database for English. Nouns, verbs, adjectives and adverbs are grouped into sets of cognitive synonyms (synsets), each expressing a distinct concept. Synsets are interlinked by means of conceptual-semantic and lexical relations. The resulting network of meaningfully related words and concepts can be navigated with the browser. WordNet superficially resembles a thesaurus, in that it groups words together based on their meanings. However, there are some important distinctions. First, WordNet interlinks not just word forms - strings of letters - but specific senses of words. As a result, words that are found in close proximity to one another in the network are semantically disambiguated. Second, WordNet labels the semantic relations among words, whereas the groupings of words in a thesaurus does not follow any explicit pattern other than meaning similarity. WordNet's structure makes it a useful tool for building a controlled vocabulary (CV). Ontomatica used WordNet to build parts of Vocal (Vocabularium Alimentarum - Vocabulary of Food). URL: http://wordnet.princeton.edu/.

WEB327

Wikipedia. Internet of Things. last accessed: 17-Nov-2014. Wikipedia link about Internet of Things (IoT) - interconnection of uniquely identifiable devices within the existing Internet infrastructure. Device interconnection is expected to enable new levels of automation. In the fields of food, nutrition and health, 'things' may be devices that monitor well-being and act as emergency notification systems. Devices may range from blood and heart rate monitors to specialized implants, such as pacemakers or hearing aids. Devices also may be agents that ensure proper treatment is administered, such as non-allergic foods or time- and food-sensitive drugs. IoT also includes data used by devices. Semantic Web applications make uniquely identifiable data 'addressable' through naming protocols, such as Uniform resource identifiers (URI). Data 'things' do not converse, but may be acted upon by other agents, such as embedded devices and centralized servers working for their human owners. URL: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_of_things.

This enables data from different sources to be connected and queried. Tim Berners-Lee, director of the World Wide Web Consortium, coined the term in a design note discussing issues around the Semantic Web project. URL: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linked_Open_Data.

WEB339

Wikipedia. Ontology. last accessed: 17-Nov-2014. Wikipedia link about ontology - a formal way to represent entities, ideas, and events (a.k.a. things or objects). Things have properties such as names and values. Things have relationships such as kinship and sequence of steps to perform a task. Things, properties and relationships are organized by categories. 'Knowledge' - in a form that can be processed by a computer - is the categorical ordering of things, properties and relationships for a specific topic. URL: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ontologies.

WEB340

Wikipedia. Open Biomedical Ontologies (OBO). last accessed: 17-Nov-2014. Wikipedia link about Open Biomedical Ontologies (OBO) - an effort to create controlled vocabularies for shared use across different biological and medical domains. OBO Ontology library forms the basis of the OBO Foundry, a collaborative experiment involving a group of ontology developers who have agreed in advance to the adoption of a growing set of principles specifying best practices in ontology development. These principles are designed to foster interoperability of ontologies within the broader OBO framework, and also to ensure a gradual improvement of quality and formal rigor in ontologies, in ways designed to meet the increasing needs of data and information integration in the biomedical domain. Ontomatica imports several Open Biomedical Ontologies. See Advice for detail. URL: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Open_Biomedical_Ontologies.

WEB350

Wikipedia. Semantic Web. last accessed: 17-Nov-2014. Wikipedia link about Semantic Web - a system that enables computers to 'understand' and respond to complex human requests. Term was coined by Tim Berners-Lee. When vision is implemented, computers will perform more of the tedious work involved in finding, combining, and acting upon information on the World Wide Web. However, implementation of vision requires that information sources be semantically structured. Standards for semantic data structures are led by World Wide Web Consortium (W3C). By encouraging inclusion of semantic content in web pages, W3C aims at converting the current web, dominated by unstructured and semi-structured documents, into a 'web of data.'. URL: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semantic_web.

WEB351

Wikipedia. Semantic network. last accessed: 17-Nov-2014. Wikipedia link about semantic network (SN) - a network for documenting relationships among concepts and for representing knowledge. SN is a directed graph consisting of vertices or nodes that represent concepts, and edges or arcs that represent relationships. The arcs and nodes can be organized into a taxonomic hierarchy. An example is WordNet, a lexical database of English. It groups English words into sets of synonyms called synsets. Synsets document semantic relations among synonyms. Examples are meronymy (A is part of B, i.e. B has A as a part of itself), holonymy (B is part of A, i.e. A has B as a part of itself), hyponymy (A is subordinate of B; A is kind of B), hypernymy (A is superordinate of B), synonymy (A denotes the same as B) and antonymy (A denotes the opposite of B). URL: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semantic_network.
